Title: AIR STRIKE Trailer #1 NEW (2018) Bruce Willis, Adrien Brody Action Movie HD
Comment:
You have a lot of people commenting here who's expectations are entirely to high.

This movie is a Chinese Movie with Chinese Stars.  The Westerners are just there for their names - though - Bruce Willis is essentially playing Claire Chennault - the guy who created the Flying Tigers.

He did do something like this - working with the Chinese Air Force to try and protect Chung King (Wade Giles Romanization) from Japanese Air Attack.  So the film is based on a historic period of time.

I had no problem with the CGI ... if someone's seen better - good for them - but it's not as bad as the boo sayer's posting here make it out. In fact - the aerial combat is the best part of the film.

They do portray the aircraft the Chinese Air Force had - which weren't very good - but it is interesting that they do show them. The Japanese Aircraft also appear to be right - except for maybe the A6M's.  The Japanese Army and Navy both had aircraft in China - but the Japanese Navy was mostly flying A5M's.

Anyway - there have been a ton of Western Movies about WWII - so it's nice to see something about China.  The Chinese suffered terribly in that war and I think it's good that they are making some movies about it.

Of course - remember - this is Chinese Communist Propaganda.

But if you take this in the same vein as some of the Russian Movies that have come out - like White Tiger - this movie isn't that bad and it is interesting to get to see the Chinese side of things.

If you're comparing it to a modern Hollywood product - it's going to come up short but for what it is - it's not that bad.
.

Title: AIR STRIKE Trailer #1 NEW (2018) Bruce Willis, Adrien Brody Action Movie HD
Comment:
True events were. In 1937 Chennault helped set up a training program for Chinese pilots before the forming of the Flying Tigers in 1941. They mostly flew the I-15 and I-16 from the USSR between 1937 and 1940 along with some Curtiss Hawk III biplanes.  They also had a few Gloster Gladiators, P-26 Peashooters, and Fiat Cr.32s obtained between 1932 and 1937. However, from 1937-1940, the USSR supplied most of their aircraft.

According to "Soviet Fighters in the Sky of China IV (1937-1940), by Anatolii Demin and A. Kosmonavtika", by the beginning of September 1938, China received from the Union of Socialist Soviet Republics 361 aircraft, of which 238 were I-15 and I-16 fighter planes. Together with the US and other foreign planes, the Chinese Air Force had a total of 602 aircraft. By the beginning of 1939, according to Chinese information, the Chinese Air Force had less than 100 aircraft of various types. A new group of 30 USSR I-15s arrived in Lanzhou on 18 July, while 30 USSR I-16s arrived on 3 August 1939. 

There was even a squadron of Soviet "volunteer" fighter pilots flying in China until 1940. (probably not in the movie). They flew the I-16.

China was sent a few Curtiss Hawk 75's to use in early 1940 (Upgrade of the P-36)

They did a fair job against the Nate (not a good job, a fair one). But when the Oscar (nick named the Army Zero by the US) started showing up in the skies in late 1939 to early 1940, the Chinese Air Force, such as it was, was decimated.

Not shown in the film will be the Soviet "volunteer" pilots that flew in China until Barbarossa started.

Chennualt is still held in honor in China, hence the Bruce Willis role.

So everyone thinking the soviet planes and other things shown are historically inaccurate, you need to do some research before opening your yap.

It looks as though all of his scenes were filmed at home, using a green screen where necessary. Yipee-ki-yay indeed.
